
A guide to medieval weapons from Europe

  In the following list WC is tohit/penetration. CODE consists of
up to 4 letters, the first representing the grip while the others
represent type(s) of damage. These are:

one of:                            any of:     
     B -- both hands needed             I -- impaling weapon
     R -- right hand only               S -- slashing weapon
     L -- left hand only                B -- bludgeoning weapon
     A -- any hand

 WEAPONTYPE        CODE     WC       DESCRIPTION
-------------------------------------------------------------------------

 KNIVES:

knife              A-S     10/11   : short bladed weapon with a single
                                     cutting edge
ballock knife      A-S     10/12   : a knife with two large protuberances
                                     where the grip joins blade, there is also
                                     a two-edged version (dagger)

dagger             A-IS    14/14   : short bladed weapon with two cutting
                                     edges and a blade tapering to a point
rondel dagger      A-IS    14/15   : a dagger with a pommel and crossguard 
                                     that are round discs of metal
dirk               A-IS    14/13   : late version of the ballock knife, used
                                     by the highlanders
swiss dagger       A-IS    14/15   : a dagger with a pommel and crossguard
                                     that are half-moon shaped
main gauche        L-IS    14/14   : a dagger with a large downward curved
                                     crossguard, used in the left hand in
                                     conjunction with a sword
cinquedea          A-IS    16/14   : a large and broad dagger

stilleto           A-I     12/16   : a thin and narrow bladed weapon
misericord         A-I     12/16   : a stilleto used to give the 
                                     coup-de-grace to a stunned opponent
bodkin             A-I     12/14   : a stilleto without edge

 SWORDS:

curved swords:
scramasax          A-S     18/19   : early single-edged shortsword

falchion           A-S     21/25   : single-edged, heavy slashing sword
scimitar           A-S     30/21   : single-edged, light slashing sword

straight swords:
gladius            A-I     21/16   : double-edged shortsword

longsword          A-S     25/23   : early longsword, slashing only
longsword          A-IS    29/25   : ordinary longsword, the common sword of
                                     the knights

two-handed swords:
courtelas          B-S     27/30   : a curved hand-and-half sword
bastard sword      B-IS    33/28   : also known as hand-and-half sword,
                                     broad double-edged, mostly slashing
estoc              B-I     22/21   : thrusting only, without edge
two-handed sword   B-S     32/32   : double-edged heavy sword

very late medieval swords:
broadsword         A-S     28/27   : broad slashing sword
rapier             A-I     35/20   : light narrow blade

 AXES:

hand axe           A-S     15/19   : normal tool 
beard axe          A-S     16/22   : early axe, developed as tool
battle axe         A-S     22/29   : the axe is usually balanced by a small
                                     hammer at the back

broad axe          B-S     21/37   : a two-handed axe used by the Danes when
                                     they conquered England
bardiche           B-S     20/31   : a long curved axe-head, the lower end
                                     of the blade is fastened to the shaft
lochaber axe       B-IS    24/35   : the end of the axe blade can be used
                                     to impale with, a hook is on the back

 CLUBS:

wooden club        A-B     16/8    : big stick
spiked club        A-IB    20/17   : metal spikes, wooden handle
flail              A-B     20/15   : military version of farm tool
morningstar        A-B     24/27   : handle, chain and spiked ball
mace               A-B     29/20   : metal club with a winged head
warhammer          A-IB    21/30   : a hammer-pick, a beak to punch through
                                     armour with and on the back a large
                                     hammer head

spiked club        B-IB    21/27   : two-handed spiked club
flail              B-B     21/21   : two-handed flail
morningstar        B-B     24/35   : two-handed morningstar

 POLEARMS:

quarterstaff       B-B     34/10   : a long and stout pole

spear              B-I     22/16   : normal spear

glaive             B-S     21/28   : a single-edged blade mounted upon a pole
fauchard           B-IS    23/30   : a glaive with a bladecatcher, the end
                                     can be used to impale with
gisarme            B-IS    27/32   : a long concave edge with a hook at the
                                     back and its shaft terminates in a 
                                     spear-head

halberd            B-IS    26/39   : has a large axe blade, a spear-head at 
                                     the end and a hook on the back
luzern hammer      B-I     23/35   : a beak to punch through armour, a spear-
                                     head at the end and four small points
                                     at the back

partisan           B-I     23/19   : a broad spear-head with two small blades
                                     (ears) projecting out at the base of the
                                     spear-head
roncone            B-I     25/21   : similar to the partisan; the ears have
                                     enlarged, and they curve to point
                                     backwards
corseques          B-I     24/25   : similar to the partisan; the ears have
                                     enlarged, they are straight and pointy
military fork      B-I     22/22   : developed from the pitchfork, has two
                                     long prongs and two backward hooks to
                                     parry and catch weapons with
